Yes, there are alternative ways to open a website in a C++ SDL 2 application without relying on `SDL_Launcher`. One option is to use the `std::system` function from the `<cstdlib>` library. Here's an example:

```cpp
#include <cstdlib>

int main() {
    std::system("xdg-open https://www.test.com");
    return 0;
}
```

This code snippet uses the `std::system` function to execute a command-line command `xdg-open` (a Linux command) followed by the website URL. This command opens the URL in the default web browser.

Please note that this method is platform-dependent and relies on the `xdg-open` command, which is typically available on Linux-based systems. You might need to change the command for other operating systems (e.g., `start` for Windows).

Remember to include necessary error handling and code specific to your platform as required.

To open a website in a C++ SDL 2 application on Windows, you can use the `ShellExecute` function provided by the Windows API. Here's an example:

```cpp
#include <windows.h>

int main() {
    ShellExecute(NULL, "open", "https://www.test.com", NULL, NULL, SW_SHOWNORMAL);
    return 0;
}
```

This code snippet uses the `ShellExecute` function to open the URL in the default web browser on Windows. The first parameter is set to `NULL` for the parent window handle. The second parameter `"open"` specifies to open the URL. The third parameter is the website URL, and the remaining parameters are set to `NULL` or default values.

Remember to include the necessary headers (`<windows.h>`) and compile the code using a C++ compiler compatible with Windows.

If you encounter linking errors, make sure to link the `Shell32.lib` library in your project settings.

